    <TD><FONT class=3Dbody face=3DArial,Verdana,SanSerif>
      <P><B>Power rating:</B><BR>The horsepower required to drive a =
machine is=20
      typically referred to as motor load. The most common equation for =
power=20
      based on torque and rotational speed is: hp =3D (torque X =
rpm)/5,250.=20
      <P>If load is not constant and follows a definite cycle, a =
horsepower=20
      versus time curve for the driven machine is helpful. From this =
curve both=20
      peak and rms horsepower can be determined. Rms load horsepower =
indicates=20
      the necessary continuous motor rating. Peak load horsepower is not =

      necessarily an indication of the required motor rating. However, =
when a=20
      peak load is maintained for a period of time, the motor rating =
usually=20
      should not be less than peak load horsepower. =
</FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD>&nbsp;</TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD><FONT class=3Dbody face=3DArial,Verdana,SanSerif><B>Duty=20
      cycle:</B><BR>Continuous steady-running loads over long periods =
are=20
      demonstrated by fans and blowers. On the other hand, machines with =

      flywheels may have wide variations in running loads. Often, the =
flywheel=20
      supplies the energy to do the work, and the motor does nothing but =
restore=20
      lost energy to the flywheel. Therefore, choosing the proper motor =
also=20
      depends on whether the load is steady, varies, follows a =
repetitive cycle=20
      of variation, or has pulsating torque or shocks.=20
      <P>For example, motors that run continuously in fans and blowers =
for hours=20
      or days may be selected on the basis of continuous load. But =
devices like=20
      automatically controlled compressors and pumps start a number of =
times per=20
      hour. And motors in some machine tools start and stop many times =
per=20
      minute.=20
      <P>Duty cycle is a fixed repetitive load pattern over a given =
period of=20
      time which is expressed as the ratio of on-time to cycle period. =
When=20
      operating cycle is such that the motor operates at idle or a =
reduced load=20
      for more than 25% of the time, duty cycle becomes a factor in =
sizing the=20
      motor. Also, energy required to start a motor (that is, =
accelerating the=20
      inertia of the motor as well as the driven load) is much higher =
than for=20
      steady-state operation, so frequent starting could overheat the =
motor.=20
      <P>For most motors (except squirrel-cage motors during =
acceleration and=20
      plugging) current is almost directly proportional to developed =
torque. At=20
      constant speed, torque is proportional to horsepower. For =
accelerating=20
      loads and overloads on motors that have considerable droop, =
equivalent=20
      horsepower is used as the load factor. The next step in sizing the =
motor=20
      is to examine motor performance curves to see if the motor has =
enough=20
      starting torque to overcome machine static friction, to accelerate =
the=20
      load to full running speed, and to handle maximum overload.=20
  </FONT></P></TD></TR>
