    <TD><FONT class=3Dbody face=3DArial,Verdana,SanSerif><B>Service=20
      factors:</B><BR>A change in NEMA standards for service factors and =

      temperature rise has been brought about because of better =
insulation. For=20
      instance, a 1.15 service factor -- once standard for all open =
motors -- is=20
      no longer standard above 200 hp.=20
      <P>Temperature rises are measured by the resistance method in the=20
      temperature rise table. Motor nameplate temperature rise is always =

      expressed for the maximum allowable load. That is, if the motor =
has a=20
      service factor greater than unity, the nameplate temperature rise =
is=20
      expressed for the overload. Two Class-B insulated motors having =
1.15 and=20
      1.25 service factors will, therefore, each be rated for a =
90=C2=B0C rise. But=20
      the second motor will have to be larger than the first in order to =

      dissipate the additional heat it generates at 125% load.=20
      <P>Service factor indicates how much over the nameplate rating a =
motor can=20
      be driven without overheating. NEMA Standard MGI-143 defines =
service=20
      factor of an ac motor as "...a multiplier which, when applied to =
the rated=20
      horsepower, indicates a permissible horsepower loading which may =
be=20
      carried under the conditions specified for the service factor..." =
In other=20
      words, multiplying nameplate horsepower by the service factor =
tells how=20
      much the motor can be overloaded without overheating. Generally, =
service=20
      factors:=20
      <UL>
        <LI>Handle a known overload, which is occasional.=20
        <LI>Provide a factor of safety where the environment or service=20
        condition is not well defined, especially for general-purpose =
motors.=20
        <LI>Obtain cooler-than-normal motor operation at rated load, =
thus=20
        lengthening insulation life. </LI></UL></FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
